{"actual_usd":0.124765,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":161,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—always.\" *I brush a thumb through the flour on my apron and lean one hip against the worktable, the oven giving off that steady brick-warmth at my side.* \"At his baptism, God wasn't promoting an ordinary man into Sonship. He was declaring who Jesus already was.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through plain.* \"Same with being divine. He didn't become divine at some point, the way dough rises into something it wasn't. He was always the Son, always one with the Father, and then in time he took on flesh and was born as a man. Baptism was revelation, not adoption.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short Bible-and-church-history version of why Christians say that.\"","rolling_24h_usd":32.89594000000002,"run_id":"849e733a-172c-467c-a5ee-3622ec117554"}
